Nov 18 2009 	A Great Place with Kids	My husband and I stayed at Hotel Kabuki-formerly Hotel Miyako-During chilly July 07 with our 3 month old and my mother. Our first family vacation and it was wonderful. At first I was hesitant to stay in Japantown, just ignorant really, but it was such a nice surprise!  Finding the hotle was a snap, but parking was valet only $35/day at the time. Check-in took about 5 minutes, really quick, and the elevator whisked us up to our rooms. We stayed in a Deluxe View Corner King room with a beautiful view-instead of curtains we had shoji screns for window coverings which are excellent blackout screens. My mom was across the hall in her own King room with a view. We were visiting during a construction phase, but you would never know. We seemed to be separated from any guests, I think we were the only guests on our floor, and that was fine with us-peace and quiet with our baby! They provided a crib for us, just a basic drop side, and since she didn't move around at all, we were not worried about crib recalls. The King bed was huge, bigger than a normal king-maybe a California King :) and we slept very peacefully in the nice bedding and pillows. The TV was nice, but I think they have updated to LCD TV's since our trip. The bathroom with the huge/deep soaking tub was a treat. Even the baby enjoyed her Japanese baths!The restaurant/lounge was not open during the construction, so we went to the mall and ate at BennyHanna's and the Sushi Boat in the Miyako Mall. The area outdoors is very nicely manicured: Peace Garden and Koi Pond. and there are several shops, restaurants (Pizza, Denny's), art galleries within walking distance, but be aware that it is hilly and steep, 4-6 blocks feels like 10 on those inclines! The amenities were scarce when we were there, no spa or in room services, no pool-still no pool, but we did have wireless internet and a morning paper.Very Kid friendly hotel: always greeting us and asking if we needed anything for the baby. And we did end up buying formula/diapers at a local Japanese market-just like a local Dallas maket with more Japanese variety, but they did carry Similac and Pampers. We walked a lot on the trip and San Fran in general is a great stroller city. Wine country/Napa not so much. Who takes their baby on a wine tour anyway?!? That's right we did, but it was OK.All in all, I would love to go back to see the updated version of this property. It was very nice and clean and steeped in Japanese decor,and I would like to see all the new amenities and room improvements.	
