Jun 24 2009 	THE place to stay in SF	We did a lot of research before deciding to spend our 4nights in SF at Hotel Kabuki. In retrospect, this was a great choice!Value - great value with respect to other comparable hotels we had considered. This is a legitimate 3.5 hotel in my opinion, in a great part of the city. We got a great internet rate of $90/night for deluxe-view room, which was lower than any comparable hotels in Fisherman's Wharf, Union Square area, or Embarcadero. Plus, this hotel comes with free internet and in-room fridge; self-parking is only $15/day. Most Union Sqr and Wharf hotels charge $30-$50 parking per day. To boot, they upgraded us to Corner View Room for free!Room - our Corner View Room was on the 10th floor, and it was great. Very spacious room, nice comfy bed, nice bed linens, thick bath towels, clean carpet. As others have commented, the bathroom was magnificent. Separate shower and deep sunken tub next to each other. The tub is just great to soak in. The bath salt that they provide, though, is not that great. You can actually get the real Japanese hot spring bath salts (sold in packaged box) at the nearby store in Miyako Mall called Ichiban-Kan. Those are much better. The room does show some wear and tear in certain spots, but is overall well-kept. The biggest problem was that the free wireless internet had extremely spotty connection.Location - we were under the impression that Union Square or Fisherman's Wharf area might be the best locations in the city. But in hindsight Hotel Kabuki's location worked out the best. The Union Square area has a lot of brand-name stores and is convenient to the BART and to Chinatown, etc. But we were not in SF to check out brand-name stores, and there's a lot of homeless presence in that area. Fisherman's Wharf area is just too hectic and touristy. On the other hand, Hotel Kabuki is connected to Japantown malls which have loads of great Japanese shops and restaurants (recommend Sophie's Crepes for great crepes and gelatos, and Benihana or Mifune for lunch). You can enter the eastern end of Japantown mall directly from the hotel lobby and then walk across the malls out the western end and you'll be right in Fillmore District that has loads of cafes, eateries and shops lining Fillmore St... this is one of the coolest hangout streets in SF. 20minute walk north from the hotel will get you to Union St, another street filled with shops and cafes.Service - the free room upgrade was a major plus. On the down-side, there were many basic things that we had a hard time getting them to supply us with. Like the shampoo... they never gave us new shampoos, even after we ran out on the third night. Another time we needed plates but the front desk told us it'd be a while before we could get them because both the restaurant and the room-service were closed that day and every housekeeping staff was busy. Ended up taking over 30minutes to get a plate and nearly as long to get the extra shampoo. I don't know if the place is short-handed or what. Housekeeping's pretty good overall, but a little bit quirky... like not supplying new shampoos at all and one day giving us less number of towels. But all in all, these were not major issues.	
